Seems to me a lot depends on the specifics. I've heard this situation
likened to someone reading your newspaper over your shoulder while
travelling on public transport - annoying but no biggie.
I don't have a wi-fi connection myself but I understand there are different
packages for the broadband connection that usually goes with it. If I was
paying a set charge for an unlimited service I wouldn't care if someone
going past my house piggy-backed it, unless that would in some way restrict
*my* access if I wanted to be on at the same time. But if I was on a capped
connection (eg limit 50Gb per month or whatever) then I'd care very much if
someone took a big bite out of that by downloading the first series of
&quot;Heroes&quot; and leaving me with barely enough capacity to read Opus.
But the general response over here seems to be that you can easily protect
your connection from this kind of intrusion so you shouldn't cry if you
haven't and someone takes advantage - bit like leaving your front door wide
open while you go to the shops.
--
John Dean
Oxford
