If by &quot;illegal in the US&quot; you mean is it a federal crime, the answer is
maybe. It's been argued that it's a violation of the federal computer
crime statute although I don't recall hearing anyone prosecuted under
that. I suspect if they were it was in relation to another crime and
they were piling on charges.

If you mean is it a violation of any state laws the answer is yes,
although I don't know of any comprehensive list of state computer laws
which you can easily browse like those &quot;age of legal consent in all 50
states&quot; charts. There certainly have been prosecutions of people solely
for piggybacking wifi in the US. In the cases I've heard of the people
have received traffic ticket level fines. A fast google showed me
convictions in MI and IL for starters.

I know at one point a New York legislator was trying to make it illegal
to set up an unsecured wifi access point which would have made the
piggybackee a criminal as well. I'm not sure if that actually made it
into law though. Once again, Google is my friend. Here's a link to the
actual announcement...

