">

By process of elimination someone has the least secure wifi network and
I bet if you found it you could have your way with their computers.

Some routers allow remote administration but I've never seen one that
had it on by default. If someone was stupid enough to turn that on while
at the same time not setting an administrators password for said router
then yeah, you could &quot;take over&quot; their connection and set a password.

If you are connecting to their wifi access point and it's configured in
a common manner you have &quot;access&quot; to other computers on their LAN.
You'll have to guess their internal IP addresses but there are some
pretty common ones to try. If they then had remote desktop connections
or ssh connections or whatever enabled for one of their machines and it
wasn't password protected you could log in to their machines and do what
you will.

Which is why if you're going to set up an unsecured access point you
should really know what you're doing to secure the rest of your network.
I need access to my machines from remote locations but I have it set up
so you can only ssh in to the machines if you are first using an
encrypted vpn using preshared keys to connect to the router and then
once inside you can only ssh in to machines where you've preshared a
public/private key (i.e. no password based logins allowed). Many times a
day I log someone trying to ssh in by blasting thousands of common
name/password pairs at my network. Even with the security I have if a
competent hacker really wanted access to my machines I assume he could
get them.

There was a pretty notorious incident earlier this year which
illustrates the danger. Hackers broke into kiosks which accepted
employment applications at TJX and from there were able to access the
corporate network including credit card records. The corporate firewalls
weren't protecting against internal access and the kiosks were
considered internal.
