Opus the Penguin &lt;opusthepenguin+use ... @gmail.com&gt; wrote:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;Third question while I'm at it. If I use someone's unsecured wireless
&gt;connection, can I take over their computer? Can I at least take over
&gt;their connection and set a password?
">

You are inside their first (and for many, only) firewall.  The routers
don't accept commands from the WAN side of the connection, but do
accept such connections from the inside.  In most cases, the inside
(&quot;LAN&quot;) side of the connection still has the password assigned by the
designers at the factory.  In such cases, you can take over the
router, set passwords, deny connections to the owner's computers, turn
off the firewall etc.  But doing any of these makes it more likely
that the owner realizes something is wrong and hiring someone with the
skills to lock down their system.

Taking over their computer?  Most of these routers are not used for
file networking, so there's not a lot of chance to implant hooks into
their systems that way.  But since you're inside the hardware
firewall, you have a lot more of Windows exposed to your hacking
prowess.  And if they ARE doing file sharing of more than just a
well-defined &quot;share&quot; directory, then you probably can do something.

It's a long time since the early days of always-on internet
connections.  I remember arguing with someone that he should password
protect his file shares.  He had two computers on a local net.  When
he got an ADSL modem he just plugged it into his existing hub and
changed his computers to pick up IP addresses from the telco.  After
failing to convince him to change his mind about file share passwords,
I went home, plugged his email address into Windows &quot;find a computer
on the network&quot; query and linked to his C drive.  I added a command
saying &quot;You really are vulnerable here.  Press enter to continue&quot; to
his bootup script (autoexec.bat).  This was, of course, before
networks of slave computers took over the email systems of the world.
